As we can see, the describe function shows some statistical info about our CSV's dataframe.
Only the numeric columns are included here.

Each table row reports a property of the corresponding column's data:

  • count: The number of the data.
  • mean: The average of the data.
  • std: The standard deviation of the data.
  • min: The minimum data.
  • 25%: The first quartile of the column's data.
  • 50%: The median of the column's data.
  • 75%: The third quartile of the column's data.
  • max: The maximum data.

3. Missing Data and NaN¶

In [ ]:

Using isna, we get a table in which each row gets a true or false value indicating whether the row's value for a column is missing and NaN.
The sum function will give us how many true values we have in the columns.

So the result is the number of NaNs in each column.
Only Age, Cabin and Embarked have missing values.

In [ ]:
dataframe['Age'].fillna(dataframe['Age'].mean(), inplace=True)
dataframe['Embarked'].fillna(dataframe['Embarked'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
dataframe.drop(columns=['Cabin'], inplace=True)

dataframe[dataframe.columns].isna().sum()
Out[ ]:

SibSp          0
Parch          0
Ticket         0

Embarked       0

We will fill the Age and Embarked columns' missing values with something appropriate.
For Age which is numerical, we will use the mean and for Embarked which is categorical, we will use the mode.
As for the Cabin column, since there are too many NaNs, we will simply remove it.

Now we print NaN counts to show that they have been filled.

While using the average to fill NaNs is simple to do and the mean is a good representative of the data as a whole, sometimes it may not make sense and be impossible to use for a column and mode or median is preferred.
Another thing in using the column mean to fill for every row is that there may be some correlation between the other columns for that row and the mean may not be have a realistic or meaningful value when put next to them.

8. Mean with Loops¶

In [ ]:
def mean_for():
    sum, total = 0, 0
    for i, row in dataframe.iterrows():
        if row['Embarked'] == 'Q':
            sum += row['Fare']
            total += 1
    return sum / total

mean_for()
Out[ ]:
13.276029870129872

Here we do the same thing as the previous question (get the fare mean of passengers who embarked in Queenstown) but with for loops.

Now we will time both approaches (vectorization and for loop) and compare them:

In [ ]:
from timeit import timeit

TIMEIT_LOOPS = 100

tvec = timeit(mean_vec, number=TIMEIT_LOOPS)
tfor = timeit(mean_for, number=TIMEIT_LOOPS)

display(tvec / TIMEIT_LOOPS)
display(tfor / TIMEIT_LOOPS)

0.00030458000001090115
0.02043183499998122

As expected, the vectorization method runs faster (about 100x here)
This is due to the compiled code behind the vectorization fuction.

10. Normalization¶

In [ ]:
def normalize(df):
    return (df - df.mean()) / df.std()

numeric_cols = dataframe.select_dtypes(include='number').columns.drop('Survived')
dataframe[numeric_cols] = normalize(dataframe[numeric_cols])

display(dataframe.hist(figsize=(20, 20)))
display(dataframe[numeric_cols].mean())
display(dataframe[numeric_cols].std())

In [ ]:
import numpy
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.stats import norm

intervals = numpy.arange(-6, 6, 0.1)

def draw(row):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    plt.title(row.name)

    plt.plot(
        intervals,
        norm.pdf(intervals, loc=row['survived_mean'], scale=row['survived_std']),
        label='survived',
        color='blue'
    )
    plt.plot(
        intervals,
        norm.pdf(intervals, loc=row['survived_not_mean'], scale=row['survived_not_std']),
        label='survived_not',
        color='red'
    )

    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

survival_df.apply(draw, axis=1);

To see which feature is better for predicting passengers' survival, we must use the one with the most difference between their diagrams for survived and not survived people's data.
The diagram for Fare has the most difference followed by Sex.
We can argue that Fare is not logically an effective factor for the survival of the people. One can say that maybe paying more gives you a more secure room but that is considered in the Pclass feature which does not have much difference.
So the Sex factor is chosen for our prediction.

12. Predicting Survival¶

In [ ]:
test_df = pandas.read_csv('Dataset/test.csv')
df_sex_row = survival_df.loc['Sex']

test_cpy = test_df.copy()
test_cpy['Sex'].replace({'male': 0, 'female': 1}, inplace=True)
normalized_test_sex = normalize(test_cpy['Sex'])

test_survived_pdf = norm.pdf(normalized_test_sex, loc=df_sex_row['survived_mean'], scale=df_sex_row['survived_std'])
test_survived_not_pdf = norm.pdf(normalized_test_sex, loc=df_sex_row['survived_not_mean'], scale=df_sex_row['survived_not_std'])
test_df['Survived'] = numpy.where(test_survived_pdf > test_survived_not_pdf, 1, 0)

test_df.to_csv('Dataset/result.csv', index=False)
display(test_df[['PassengerId', 'Sex', 'Survived']])

Here we use the Sex feature and predict whether a passenger survives or not.
We get the PDF for survived and not survived passengers (as we did for the plot in question 11)
Then for a specific sex, we check if it's in the interval where survived is higher or not survived is higher in the PDF.
And finally, a new column is added to the test dataframe and written to result.csv
